  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">David Warriner's article, \"How to Read a Paper: The Basics of Evidence-Based Medicine,\" published in the BMJ in 2008, has been cited 5 times, indicating its relevance in the field of evidence-based medicine. The research emphasizes foundational reading skills necessary for professionals engaged in scientific inquiry, thereby enhancing their critical appraisal capabilities.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Published in the BMJ in 2008, \"How to Read a Paper: The Basics of Evidence-Based Medicine\" by David Warriner has achieved a citation count of 5. This suggests that the work has had a meaningful impact on the academic community, particularly in guiding practitioners in the domain of evidence-based medicine. The article serves as a quintessential resource for understanding the pivotal methodologies and principles involved in critically evaluating scientific literature.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The work has been cited across various notable venues, such as \"Information and Software Technology\" and \"Biomedicines,\" with multiple reviews highlighting its importance in fostering a deeper comprehension of research practices in medicine. This illustrates not only the work's sustained relevance but also its influence on scholarly discussions surrounding evidence evaluation within different subfields.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">In terms of geographic reach, the citations stem primarily from scholars based in the United States, Switzerland, Italy, and India. This diverse citing landscape underscores the article's applicability and value across a wide range of contexts, enhancing the global discourse on evidence-based medical practices.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Though the work has not generated significant public mentions on platforms such as Wikipedia or Reddit, its proven downstream reuse across multiple review articles indicates that it continues to be a foundational text for subsequent research. This commitment to enabling further exploration and understanding within the field resonates with current efforts in educational and professional development in medicine.</p>",
